  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 14:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Should it be the case, however, that there is no interpreter present, let him be silent in the assembly",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This comprises the double possibility that the speaker with tongues cannot himself interpret, and also that no other, who possesses the donum interpretandi, is present. Regarding ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "εἶναι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as equivalent to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "παρεῖναι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", comp. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 8:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 2:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". David Schulz understands ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ᾖ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as the simple copula: “if, however, he does not know how to make himself intelligible.” But the interpretation might in fact be given also by another, who had the charisma of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἑρμηνεία γλωσσῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 12:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 12:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "σιγ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐν ἐκκλ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".] Paul takes for granted here—and how easily one can understand it, considering the intimate union subsisting among the Christians of those days!—that the members of the community mutually ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "know",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " each other as regards their special endowment.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἑαυτῷ δὲ λαλ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "θ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".] in contrast to addresses given ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐν τῇ ἐκκλησίᾳ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and hence a characteristic designation of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "private devotion",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " carried on by means of glossolalic prayer, where his glossolalia avails ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for himself and God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 14:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), not for others also as listeners. Comp. Epict. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Diss.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " iv. 8. 17, and the similar passages in Wetstein. Others take it to mean: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "quietly in his thoughts",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Theophylact, comp. Chrysostom, also Chr. F. Fritzsche), so that it remains on the footing of an inward intercourse between him and his God (Hofmann); which, however, is not in keeping with the essential mark of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λαλεῖν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "this being uttered aloud",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which belonged to the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "matter in hand",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".[18] Observe, further, how, even in this highest degree of inspired impulse to speak, a man could control his own will. Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 14:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[18] Besides, it was self-evident that, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "where silence was enjoined",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a man did not need to be in the first instance remitted to quiet inward fellowship with God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
